hits.description:
Accidents can happen at any time and regardless of how many precautions are taken. When an accident happens, how you respond could be the difference between life and death. In this four-module course, you will learn about what to do in an emergency, including initial responses to injury situations, first aid guidelines, and best practices.

The course also covers the AHA’s 2010 Guidelines for Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation (CPR) and Emergency Cardiovascular Care (ECC), including both full and hands-only CPR. Note that this course does not qualify students for first aid certification; it is meant to be used as a review between certifications.

Estimated duration: 45 minutes
hits.title: Basic First Aid

hits.description:
Many people would rather die than stand in front of a microphone. It doesn’t have to be that way. This brief course will show that anyone can become a polished public speaker with practice. We've designed it for the person who wants to feel confident while powerfully delivering a message to any audience, large or small.

In an introductory video presentation a voice coach shares her secret to success in public speaking. An article provides some practical tips. The course concludes with a quiz based on both the video and the article.
hits.title: How to Master Public Speaking

hits.description:
Suppose someone you work with or someone you love were to have a seizure. Would you know what was happening? Moreover, would you know what to do? In this six-module course you’ll learn the general steps to take when someone is having a seizure, and the specific first aid steps for tonic-clonic, complex partial, absence, and tonic/atonic seizures. You’ll also learn what to do if a seizure occurs in water and how to help someone who is having a seizure while in a wheelchair.

 

A short quiz follows each module, and a final assessment concludes the course.
hits.title: Seizure First Aid

hits.description: This course, intended for those who are either interviewing for a position with a new company or for a new role with their current employer, covers the fundamentals—the steps to take before, during, and after your interview.  Though many of the tips offered may feel “salesy”, the suggested approach is relevant to candidates in all spheres of business. After all, an interview is an exercise in sales – with you as the product! The course also includes two excellent TED talks, one on the topic of self-confidence, and another on the use of powerful body language, both critical to interview success. A short quiz follows each module.
hits.title: Interviewing 101

hits.description:
Until recently, epilepsy was thought of as a childhood disorder. Today, it is evident that epilepsy in people aged 75 years and older is more prevalent than in children under 10. Epilepsy is the third most common neurological disorder in the over 75 year age group, following stroke and dementia. Both of the latter  are associated with an increased incidence of epilepsy. As the world population ages, it can be predicted that there will be an increase in the numbers of older people living with epilepsy. Medical sources have estimated that by the year 2025, 50% of new-onset seizures will be in older persons.

 

This four-module course takes a thorough look at the realities of epilepsy in old age. Useful to caregivers and elderly people with epilepsy who want to know more about their condition, some of the topics explored include the causes of epilepsy in the elderly, the different types of treatments available, and safety measures for older people with epilepsy.
hits.title: Epilepsy and the Older Person
